excerpt: Open museum in a Victorian coastal fort with labyrinthine tunnels, plus film and diorama displays.
detail_description: Nothe Fort is a captivating open museum located in a Victorian coastal fort with intricate tunnels and captivating film and diorama displays. Originally constructed between 1860-1872, the fort has been repurposed into a museum showcasing coastal defense artifacts, exhibitions, and interactive displays. Visitors can immerse themselves in the historical significance of wartime technology while enjoying special events held throughout the year. Additionally, dog owners can bring their furry companions to explore the green spaces surrounding the fort.
name: Nothe Fort
address: Barrack Rd, Weymouth, DT4 8UF, United Kingdom

excerpt: Curving, sheltered beach popular for sun bathing & swimming & once frequented by King George III.
detail_description: Weymouth Beach is a popular destination in Dorset, known for its three miles of golden sands and clear blue waters. It offers stunning views of the bay and the Jurassic Coast. The beach is conveniently located just minutes from the town center and hosts various seaside events and attractions, such as the Jurassic Skyline gondola ride and Sandworld's sand sculpture festival.
name: Weymouth Beach
address: Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 8DG, United Kingdom

excerpt: Vibrant boating marina with shower facilities, a nearby sand beach & an annual seafood festival.
detail_description: Weymouth Harbour is a vibrant and bustling boating marina with a rich history dating back to Roman times. It remains a thriving destination, attracting pleasure boats and offering shower facilities. The harbor played significant roles in historical events such as the Spanish Armada and the Civil War. Visitors can enjoy the picturesque sight of fishing boats, colorful houses, and nearby sandy beaches.
name: Weymouth Harbour
address: Custom House Quay, Weymouth, DT4 8BG, United Kingdom

excerpt: Cliffside castle ruins, constructed in the 16th century, known for peaceful gardens & sea views.
detail_description: Sandsfoot Castle, a cliffside castle ruin dating back to the 16th century, is renowned for its tranquil gardens and stunning sea views. Originally built in 1539 as part of Henry VIII's coastal defense strategy, the Tudor artillery castle was eventually abandoned by the military in the mid-17th century.
name: Sandsfoot Castle
address: 39 Old Castle Rd, Weymouth, DT4 8QE, United Kingdom

detail_description: Sandworld is a captivating exhibition showcasing impressive sand craftsmanship in the UK. Held in Weymouth, this event takes place under a massive marquee where talented artists continuously work on new pieces throughout the season. Visitors can even try their hand at sand sculpting under the guidance of internationally renowned experts. This family-friendly attraction features towering sand sculptures, some reaching over 12 feet tall, with a new display created each year.
name: Weymouth Beach Sand Sculptures
address: 32 Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 8EA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Tranquil, scenic nature preserve with wetlands & paths for viewing waterfowl, such as swans & ducks.
detail_description: RSPB Radipole Lake is a serene nature reserve located in the heart of Weymouth, offering picturesque wetlands and pathways for observing various waterfowl species like swans and ducks. The reserve features a family-friendly discovery center housed in a charming thatched cottage, providing information about the diverse birdlife that can be spotted from the wooden walkways across the wetlands.
name: RSPB Radipole Lake
address: Radipole Park Dr, Weymouth, DT4 7TZ, United Kingdom

excerpt: Family-friendly exhibits with a variety of sea creatures (most offer play areas & group packages).
detail_description: SEA LIFE Centre Weymouth is a renowned tropical paradise in the heart of a vibrant city, offering family-friendly exhibits with a variety of sea creatures. Visitors can explore coral caves, lagoons, and ocean depths to marvel at sharks, stingrays, otters, seahorses, and giant crabs. The park is known for its great conservation work and features rescued sea turtles, seals, penguins (including Fairy Penguins), sharks, rays, and more.
name: SEA LIFE Centre Weymouth
address: Lodmoor Country Park, Weymouth, DT4 7SX, United Kingdom

detail_description: Tudor House Museum in Weymouth is a well-preserved 17th-century building located on Trinity Street, which used to be part of the old harbor. The three-story house was built at the beginning of the 17th century and features traditional double gable architecture. Originally situated by the water's edge, it now stands as a museum furnished to resemble a 17th-century home.
name: Tudor House Museum, Weymouth
address: Tudor House, 3 Trinity St, Weymouth DT4 8TW, United Kingdom

excerpt: Large public park with trails & playgrounds, plus attractions such as a mini-train ride & aquarium.
detail_description: Lodmoor Country Park, located in Weymouth, Dorset, England, is a sprawling 300-acre public park offering a wide range of recreational activities and leisure facilities. Visitors can enjoy nature trails, picnic areas with barbecue spots, playgrounds for children, and even a cafe and pub serving hot food. The park also features attractions such as a mini-train ride and an aquarium. Additionally, it hosts various events including car rallies and circuses.
name: Lodmoor Country Park
address: Weymouth, DT4 7SX, United Kingdom

detail_description: Weymouth Museum, located in a Victorian Brewery off Hope Square, offers a captivating journey through the town's history with its unique exhibits and artworks. Run by volunteers, the museum specializes in local topography, trades and industry, maritime items, as well as postcards and photographs that are part of Weymouth's heritage. It provides an insightful perspective on the city's past.
name: Weymouth Museum
address: 39b St Thomas St, Weymouth, DT4 8EH, United Kingdom

excerpt: Waterside theatre for variety shows and music, plus hall staging wrestling, dance classes and more.
detail_description: Weymouth Pavilion, situated on the harbor wall at the southern end of the esplanade, has a rich history dating back to its construction in 1908 as the Ritz Theatre. Despite being requisitioned during WWII and later destroyed by fire in 1954, it still exudes vintage seaside charm. The theater hosts a variety of shows including music performances, wrestling matches, and dance classes. It is particularly popular during summer with family-friendly shows.
name: Weymouth Pavilion
address: Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 8ED, United Kingdom

detail_description: Alexandra Gardens is a small park area located on the seafront in Weymouth. It features classic arcade games, fairground rides for smaller kids, and plenty of traditional seaside entertainment. The gardens are situated near St Alban Street, a narrow road with interesting shops and food places. The area was once home to Weymouth Gardens Theatre which opened in 1924.
name: Alexandra Gardens
address: Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 8DL, United Kingdom

excerpt: Landscaped water lily garden with ponds and lakes, a Japanese bridge and a local history museum.
detail_description: Bennetts Water Gardens is a picturesque landscape featuring ponds, lakes, a Japanese bridge, and a local history museum. The gardens cover eight acres of land that was once an old brickworks clay quarry. It is home to the National Plant Collection of water lilies and offers grassy walking areas, woodland trails with wheelchair access, and a Tropical House showcasing warm-climate plants. The venue also serves as an ideal location for weddings with its vibrant colors and serene ambiance.
name: Bennetts Water Gardens
address: Putton Ln, Chickerell, Weymouth DT3 4AF, United Kingdom

detail_description: Nothe Gardens in Weymouth is a must-visit spot that offers free access to beautiful lawns, a wooden play area, and stunning views of Weymouth and Portland harbors. The gardens are located around the historic Victorian Nothe Fort, providing a picturesque setting for picnics, sports activities, and leisurely strolls. Visitors can also enjoy the presence of wildlife such as grey squirrels amidst the lush greenery.
name: Nothe Gardens
address: Weymouth, DT4 8UF, United Kingdom

excerpt: Popular swimming spot with a cliff walk along a coastline known for ancient ruins & rock formations.
detail_description: Bowleaze Cove is a picturesque shingle beach located in Weymouth, Dorset. It's a popular spot for swimming and sunbathing, with towering cliffs surrounding the small cove. The area is known for its ancient ruins and rock formations, making it an ideal destination for coastal walks and fossil hunting along the South West Coast Path. Families can enjoy the Fantasy Island Fun Park on the beach, while kite flying and dog walking are also popular activities.
name: Bowleaze Cove
address: Bowleaze Coveway, Weymouth, DT3 6PL, United Kingdom

name: Weymouth Pirate Adventure Mini Golf
address: Lodmoor Country Park, Weymouth, DT4 7SX, United Kingdom

excerpt: A rustic seaside hut with tables standing on sand belies a menu of upscale fresh seafood dishes.
detail_description: Nestled on the Jurassic Coast, Crab House Café is a charming seafood restaurant in Weymouth. The rustic seaside hut offers a laid-back atmosphere and upscale fresh seafood dishes at reasonable prices. Overlooking the Portland Coast and Chesil Beach, it specializes in serving fresh local crab on large wooden boards with all the necessary accessories. Additionally, it boasts its own oyster beds just in front of the cafe, ensuring that diners enjoy the freshest seafood experience possible.
name: Crab House Café
address: Ferrymans Way, Portland Rd, Weymouth, DT4 9YU, United Kingdom

excerpt: Small, panoramic site where the stone foundations of a 4th-century Romano-Celtic temple can be seen.
detail_description: Jordan Hill Roman Temple is a small but picturesque site located on Jordan Hill above Bowleaze Cove. It features the stone foundations of a 4th-century Romano-Celtic temple and offers panoramic views of Weymouth Bay and the surrounding countryside. The temple, now under the guardianship of English Heritage, attracts numerous tourists throughout the year. Despite only the foundations remaining, it provides an atmospheric glimpse into Roman history and is worth a visit for enthusiasts or those seeking beautiful vistas.
name: Jordan Hill Roman Temple
address: Bowleaze Coveway, Weymouth, DT3 6PL, United Kingdom

excerpt: Renovated information centre for wildlife and environmental exhibitions and boat trip bookings.
detail_description: The Dorset Wildlife Trust Wild Chesil Centre is a beautifully renovated hub dedicated to wildlife and environmental exhibitions, as well as boat trip bookings. Nestled near the stunning Lorton Meadows, this area boasts lush fields bordered by thick hedgerows and small woodlands, making it a haven for various bird species and rare wildflowers. Visitors can immerse themselves in the natural beauty of Chesil Beach and Fleet Lagoon through interactive displays that explain their unique formations and local wildlife.
name: Dorset Wildlife Trust Wild Chesil Centre
address: Portland Beach Road, Portland, DT4 9XE, United Kingdom

detail_description: If you're looking for a fantastic spot to keep the kids entertained, look no further than Sharkys Fun Factory in Weymouth. This vibrant indoor play center is perfect for children of all ages, featuring an expansive soft-play area where little ones can jump, climb, and bounce to their heart's content. With dedicated zones for toddlers under three years old, parents can relax knowing their younger children are safe while having fun.
name: Sharkys Fun Factory
address: 7 Albany Rd, Weymouth, DT4 9TH, United Kingdom

detail_description: Weymouth is a fantastic holiday destination with plenty of activities to enjoy. The pristine beach offers a clean and inviting environment, perfect for relaxing and soaking up the sun. Indulge in delicious fish and chips while taking in the beautiful coastal views.
name: Weymouth Seafront
address: S W Coast Path, Weymouth, DT4 7EA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Weymouth is a seaside town in Dorset, southern England. Its sandy beach is dotted with colorful beach huts and backed by Georgian houses. Jurassic Skyline, a revolving viewing tower, and Victorian Nothe Fort offer harbour views. Weymouth Sealife Park is home to sharks, turtles and stingrays. On the fossil-rich Jurassic Coast is pebbly Chesil Beach. A causeway leads to Portland Island with its lighthouse and birdlife.
detail_description: Weymouth, a charming seaside town in Dorset, southern England, is known for its sandy beach lined with colorful beach huts and Georgian houses. Visitors can enjoy panoramic views of the harbor from attractions like the Jurassic Skyline and Victorian Nothe Fort. The town is also home to Weymouth Sealife Park, featuring a variety of marine life.
name: Weymouth
address: United Kingdom

detail_description: Greenhill Gardens in Weymouth is a unique and picturesque spot to visit. The beach huts here are unlike any other, with quirky concrete-and-iron structures that form a double-decker row of single-cell changing huts. Built as part of an employment scheme between the wars, they add character to the promenade between the gardens and the north end of the beach.
name: Greenhill Gardens
address: Weymouth, DT4 7SG, United Kingdom

excerpt: Amusement park offering bumper cars, a ghost train & other rides, plus an arcade & a cafe.
detail_description: Fantasy Island, located in Bowleaze Cove, Weymouth, is a delightful amusement park offering a wide variety of rides and attractions suitable for the entire family. From classic favorites like bumper cars and spinning teacups to thrilling experiences such as the ghost train and flying elephants, there's something for everyone. The park also features an arcade with various games and a soft play area for younger children.
name: Southside Funfair
address: Bowleaze Coveway, Weymouth, DT3 6PW, United Kingdom

detail_description: The Rodwell Trail, a 3.5-kilometer route in Dorset, connects Ferrybridge to Weymouth and offers remnants of old railway stations and a small tunnel. The trail provides stunning views of Portland Harbour and Sandfoot Castle Gardens. Birdwatchers can visit the RSPB reserve at Radipole Lake near Weymouth Station to observe local wildlife.
name: Rodwell Trail
address: Weymouth, DT4 0AB, United Kingdom

excerpt: Horse & rider image carved into a hill, originally created in 1808 & restored in the 2010s.
detail_description: Osmington White Horse is a striking hillside carving of a horse and rider, originally created in 1808 and restored in the 2010s. It overlooks the town of Weymouth and depicts King George III, who was a beloved patron of the area. The site offers lovely views of the surrounding countryside and there's a small parking lot nearby with information about its history. Visitors can also stop by The Springhead for a meal while enjoying the picturesque surroundings.
name: Osmington White Horse
address: Weymouth, DT3 6LU, United Kingdom

excerpt: Warm, family-friendly eatery with art-lined walls offering burgers & salads plus wine, beer & cider.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Weymouth, Nautico Lounge is a delightful eatery that exudes warmth and charm. Housed in a historic post office building, this family-friendly spot boasts an inviting atmosphere adorned with vibrant artwork and colorful seating. Whether you're craving hearty burgers or fresh salads, Nautico Lounge has something for everyone, including vegetarian and vegan options as well as a special kids' menu.
name: Nautico Lounge
address: 66 St Thomas St, Weymouth, DT4 8EL, United Kingdom

excerpt: Spacious, split-level, quayside pub with bookshelves, storm lamps and an eclectic global menu.
detail_description: The Ship Inn Weymouth is a charming split-level pub located on the quayside, offering a unique atmosphere with bookshelves and storm lamps. Over the years, it has undergone changes including the addition of an upstairs restaurant boasting stunning views of Weymouth Harbour and a sunny courtyard. As part of the Hall & Woodhouse family since 1856, this picturesque pub offers an eclectic global menu.
name: The Ship Inn Weymouth
address: Custom House Quay, Weymouth, DT4 8BE, United Kingdom

detail_description: Upwey Wishing Well Tearooms & Water Gardens in Dorset is a perfect destination for a leisurely day out. Take a stroll through the enchanting water gardens, make a wish at the well, and then head to the tearoom for a delightful meal. Indulge in traditional afternoon tea or high tea with delectable handmade cakes and their famous wishing well fruit scones.
name: Upwey Wishing Well Tearooms & Water Gardens
address: 161 Church St, Weymouth, DT3 5QE, United Kingdom

detail_description: Rossi's is an iconic ice cream parlour on Weymouth's historic esplanade. The shop has been owned and operated by the Figliolini family for over seventy years, and continues to serve delicious vanilla free natural ice cream favourites. Specials change throughout the year, but a trip to Rossi's is definitely not complete without trying their famous '99!
name: Rossi's Ices
address: 92 Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 7AT, United Kingdom

detail_description: Kika Beach Club is truly a hidden treasure that promises an unforgettable experience. Whether you're stopping by for a late breakfast or enjoying cocktails with friends, the warm welcome from the staff sets the tone for your visit. The menu boasts delightful options like cured meats and cheese boards, as well as scrumptious cheesy mash croquettes that are sure to please any palate. With its stunning beachfront location, you can sip on expertly crafted cocktails while soaking in breathtaking ocean views—it's almost like being transported abroad!
name: Kika Beach Club
address: 52-53 Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 8DG, United Kingdom

excerpt: Waterway known for its reliable sailing conditions, plus birdwatching, beaches & yachting trips.
detail_description: Weymouth Bay is a picturesque waterway that offers ideal conditions for sailing and birdwatching, as well as opportunities for beach relaxation and yachting excursions. Visitors can take a leisurely stroll along the promenade, passing notable landmarks such as the Jubilee Clock and the American D-Day Memorial. The bay's stunning views are equally captivating in both sunny summer days and stormy winter weather.
name: Weymouth Bay
address: United Kingdom

detail_description: Brewers Quay, located in Weymouth, is a shopping center with various attractions. The Weymouth Museum inside Brewers Quay showcases maritime exhibits. Additionally, visitors can explore the Timewalk, featuring historical tableaux, and the interactive Discovery Centre suitable for all ages. This former Victorian brewery also offers a car park and restaurants for convenience. Once housing unique independent shops and cafes, it was a beloved tourist spot in Weymouth.
name: Brewers Quay
address: 4 Hope St, Hope Square, Weymouth, DT4 8TR, UK

detail_description: The Royal Dorset Yacht Club offers a warm and welcoming atmosphere with a beautiful view and delicious Sunday carvery. The chef and his wife provide excellent service, making guests feel at home. The club also features themed nights such as BBQ and curry, offering a variety of dining experiences. Additionally, the ground floor houses 'Delicious,' a fabulous business serving wine, gin, sharing platters, and more. Visitors can enjoy the outside space and explore the deli for delightful take-home treats.
name: Royal Dorset Yacht Club
address: 11 Custom House Quay, Weymouth, DT4 8BG, United Kingdom

excerpt: One of the world's largest manmade harbors, built in the 19th century, with 4 breakwaters.
detail_description: Portland Harbour, constructed in 1872, is one of the world's largest manmade harbors with four breakwaters. It covers a vast area of 520 hectares and was initially used for ship maintenance and as a prison barge for potential migrants. The harbor offers stunning views and is popular for water and wind sports. Visitors are advised to navigate carefully due to the presence of lone dolphins in the area. Overall, it is considered a beautiful spot with friendly staff and a picturesque setting.
name: Portland Harbour
address: United Kingdom

detail_description: Greenhill Gardens, located in the northeast suburb of Greenhill, offers a delightful array of gardens with winding pathways, vibrant floral borders, and well-maintained lawns. These gardens were originally part of the Wilton Estate before being gifted to the town in 1902.
name: Greenhill Gardens
address: Weymouth, DT4 7FN, United Kingdom

detail_description: Cafe Blue in Weymouth offers a delightful start to the day with options like a full English breakfast or skinny pancakes. The cafe's welcoming atmosphere and friendly staff create a charming experience for visitors. Guests have praised the delicious hot chocolate, cheese & onion toasty, and vegetarian breakfast. The accommodating service includes providing highchairs and even cutting up food for children.
name: Cafe Blue
address: 60 Esplanade, Weymouth, DT4 8DE, United Kingdom

excerpt: Lorton Meadows nature reserve and conservation centre, an area of grassland with harbour views.
detail_description: Lorton Meadows Nature Reserve is a stunning wildlife sanctuary located just northwest of Weymouth, offering visitors a delightful escape into nature. As dawn breaks, the serene atmosphere comes alive with the sounds of songbirds and the gentle rustle of leaves. This picturesque reserve features lush grasslands, charming hedgerows, and small woodlands that create an inviting habitat for various species. With its well-marked trails spanning approximately 2.
name: Lorton Meadows Nature Reserve
address: Lorton Ln, Weymouth, DT3 5QH, United Kingdom

detail_description: RSPB Lodmoor is a well-preserved and tranquil haven for wildlife enthusiasts, offering plenty of opportunities to get close to nature. The area provides various walking paths and abundant wildlife viewing, making it perfect for dog walkers, birdwatchers, and nature lovers. Visitors can enjoy the peaceful surroundings and observe the diverse bird population. While parking may be a bit pricey, the site's natural beauty and abundance of activities make it well worth a visit.
name: RSPB Lodmoor
address: Preston Rd, Weymouth, DT3 6HS, United Kingdom

excerpt: Sanctuary for 600 mute swans on the site of an 11th-century monastery, plus kids' play and a maze.
detail_description: Abbotsbury Swannery is a historic sanctuary for over 600 mute swans, situated on the grounds of an 11th-century monastery. The swannery, located near the charming village of Abbotsbury in Dorset, offers visitors the unique opportunity to wander among free-flying swans and witness them nesting in their natural habitat. The best time to visit is from May to June when cygnets are hatching, creating a breathtaking spectacle.
name: Abbotsbury Swannery
address: New Barn Rd, Abbotsbury, Weymouth DT3 4JG, United Kingdom

excerpt: 18th-century garden with rare plants and notable magnolia and camellia blooms, plus a restaurant.
detail_description: Abbotsbury Subtropical Gardens is a stunning 18th-century garden spread across 20 acres in a sheltered valley leading to Chesil Beach. The unique microclimate allows delicate plants to thrive, including rare camellias, magnolias, and an impressive collection of rhododendrons and hydrangeas. Originally a kitchen garden for Abbotsbury Castle, the gardens have evolved over the years and now feature a mix of formal and informal flowers.
name: Abbotsbury Subtropical Gardens
address: Bullers Wy, Abbotsbury, Weymouth DT3 4LA, United Kingdom

excerpt: Steep shingle beach, popular with anglers & walkers, with many cafes along its 18-mile length.
detail_description: Chesil Beach, made famous by Ian McEwan's novel of the same name, is an 18-mile long shingle beach stretching from West Bay to Portland. This UNESCO World Heritage Site is separated from the mainland by Fleet Lagoon and offers stunning aerial views. The area is a sanctuary for various bird species and marine life, making it a popular spot for anglers and walkers.
name: Chesil Beach
address: United Kingdom

excerpt: Unique gallery with huge sand sculptures & a sand pit for hands-on creations, plus a coffee shop.
detail_description: Sandworld Weymouth is a captivating gallery featuring impressive sand sculptures and a hands-on sand pit for visitors to unleash their creativity. The exhibition showcases the remarkable work of renowned sand sculptors, with themes changing annually. This year's display revolves around sci-fi films and TV series, offering an opportunity to witness artists crafting their masterpieces throughout the season. Additionally, the venue houses a charming coffee shop for guests to relax and enjoy refreshments.
name: Sandworld Weymouth
address: Preston Beach Road Lodmoor Country Park, Weymouth, DT4 7SX, United Kingdom

detail_description: The Jurassic Safari is an exciting tourist attraction that offers an ATV safari experience. Visitors can book their trips over the phone with friendly staff who are quick to answer any questions. During the safari, participants get to see various creatures and animals, including sheep and other exotic species that are expertly shown by experienced guides like Gary. The trip is both informative and fun for adults and children alike, as they learn about what they see along the way.
name: Jurassic Safari
address: Park Farm, Wanchard Ln, Charminster, Dorchester DT2 9RP, United Kingdom

detail_description: St Catherine's Chapel is a picturesque location in the village of Abbotsbury, offering stunning views along Chesil Beach and the Jurassic Coast. A leisurely walk up the hill leads to the chapel, which stands out prominently and provides panoramic views of the countryside and ocean. The interior is bathed in beautiful light during summer evenings, making it a great spot for photography or simply relaxing on the grass while enjoying the peaceful ambiance.
name: St. Catherine’s Chapel
address: Abbotsbury, Weymouth, DT3 4JH, United Kingdom

detail_description: Kings Statue is conveniently located on the Weymouth seafront, easily accessible from the Mount Pleasant Park and Ride. Parking can be a challenge in Weymouth, but there are short-stay car parks available near the Gurkha restaurant. Additionally, a park and ride option at Mount Pleasant provides a hassle-free way to reach Kings Statue while enjoying the scenic coastal views.
name: Kings Statue
address: Weymouth, DT4 8DE, UK

detail_description: Nestled in the picturesque village of Abbotsbury, Dansel Gallery is a treasure trove for art enthusiasts and lovers of craftsmanship. This delightful gallery showcases an impressive array of unique woodwork created by over 200 talented designer-makers from across the UK. Each piece reflects exceptional woodworking skills and emphasizes sustainable timber use, making it not just a shopping destination but also a celebration of eco-friendly artistry.
name: Dansel Gallery
address: Rodden Row, Abbotsbury, Weymouth DT3 4JL, United Kingdom

detail_description: Abbotsbury Playground is a delightful gem nestled in a scenic location, perfect for families seeking outdoor fun. Established in 2006 through the generous contributions of the community and various grants, this playground has been lovingly maintained by dedicated volunteers who ensure it remains clean and safe for children. With an array of play equipment suitable for kids aged 3-6, it's an inviting space where little ones can explore and enjoy themselves.
name: Abbotsbury Playground
address: Seaway Ln, Abbotsbury, Weymouth DT3 4JT, United Kingdom

detail_description: The Weymouth Land Train offers two engaging tours for visitors to explore the town. The lime-green train runs every half an hour, traveling at a leisurely 10mph along the road from the Esplanade to Hope Square. Travelers can choose between a history tour that covers the old side of town, Nothe Fort, and various museums, or a harbor tour with a musical theme featuring sea shanty performances.
name: Weymouth train seafront
address: Weymouth, DT4 8EA, United Kingdom

detail_description: Weymouth is home to several war memorials, each serving as a poignant reminder of the area's history. One notable structure is the cenotaph, erected in the early 1920s to honor those who perished in World War I. This memorial stands as a tribute to the 749 individuals who lost their lives during D-Day training exercises. While not easily found on Google Maps, these memorials are worth seeking out and exploring further.
name: War Memorial
address: Weymouth, DT4 7AX, United Kingdom
